Q: Programmers at the Flanky  Computer Corporation designed the protocol showned below to achive n-thread mutual exclusion.

  1. Does this protocol satisfy mutual exclusion?
  2. is this protocol starvation-free?
  3. is this protocol deadlock-free?
  4. is this protocol livelock-free?

  the lock algorithm in question:
  
  class FLaky implements Lock {
      private int turn;
      private boolean busy = false;

      public void lock() {
        int me = ThreadID.get();
        do {
          do {
            turn = me;
          } while (busy);
          busy = true;
        } while (turn != me);
      }

      public void unlock() {
        busy = false;
      }
    }




R: 1. this protocol satisfys mutual exclusion, since there wont be more then 1 thread at the CS(critical section) at the same time.
      - the first thread comes sets turn to itself
      - busy = false, so procedes
      - sets busy to true
      - turn = me so its locked

      - 2nd thread comes and sets turn to itself
      - busy = true so it will keep on setting the turn to itself until the first thread unlocks
      - ...

   2. this protocol doesnt satisfy starvation-free requesites, due to the turn logic.
      the threads waiting will keep on setting the turn to them selfs, 
      one thread (thread A) that is waiting will eventualy see the busy = false and procedes.
      In the mean time another thread (thread B) sets the turn to B.
      Thread A reaches the final while, and verifys that the turn = B (!=A), so it goes back to the beggining of the lock;

   3/4. picking up the example above, if that happens, thread A might set the busy to true, and when trying to verify the final while condition,
        it sees that turn = B so it goes back to the beggining. 
        With that the busy = true so all threads will be waiting infinitely. (The thread that was supposed to unlock it was A, but it failed the final verification).

